            </div>
          </div>
          <p><strong>Picture this: Your dog bolts toward the boundary line. The GPS drifts 15 feet. Your boundary is now in the road. That's not a hypothetical &mdash; it happened during my testing with one of these collars.</strong></p>
          <p>When I tested both systems by walking the exact same boundary 10 times over 2 weeks, the difference was staggering:</p>
          <div class="vs-grid">
            <div class="vs-card vs-winner">
              <h4>SpotOn Performance</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Under 5 feet accuracy in open areas (third-party tested)</li>
                <li>8-12 feet under heavy tree cover</li>
                <li>11x less GPS drift than previous generation</li>
                <li>99.3% containment rate (third-party tested)</li>
                <li>Consistent in rain and cloudy conditions</li>
                <li>No random drift or shifting boundaries</li>
                <li>Forest Mode for densely wooded areas</li>
                <li>True Location&trade; technology</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="vs-card">
              <h4>Halo Collar 5 Performance</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Dual-frequency L1+L5 GPS, AlwaysOn GPS, 20 updates/sec</li>
                <li>2-3 meters open sky; 3-5 ft drift under moderate tree cover</li>
                <li>15-25+ feet under heavy tree cover</li>
                <li>On-board AI processing for location</li>
                <li>Boundaries shifted during cloudy weather</li>
                <li>Some drift near buildings</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p><strong>The Technical Reason SpotOn Wins:</strong> SpotOn Nova's 5x larger active dual-band, dual-feed antenna connects to 151 satellites across GPS, GLONASS, Galileo, and Beidou using True Location&trade; technology while constantly filtering interference.</p>
          <p><strong>Why This Matters More Than Anything Else:</strong> Even 10 feet of boundary inaccuracy could put your dog in the path of a car, on a neighbor's property, or lost in unfamiliar territory. Accuracy isn't a feature &mdash; it's the difference between a safe dog and a missing dog.</p>
          <img src="https://betterthanafence.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/Adjusting-Position-in-App-Resize-1024x682.jpg" alt="SpotOn app showing GPS boundary adjustment" width="1024" height="682" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        </div>

